For the diagonal entry (i, i), we need to show that the function (fun ω => wignerMatrixMap n ω i i) has law ν. By definition, this means that for any measurable set S in ℝ, the measure of {ω | wignerMatrixMap n ω i i ∈ S} is equal to ν(S).

But wignerMatrixMap n ω i i is just the i-th diagonal entry of the matrix. From the definition of the WignerMeasure, the diagonal entries are precisely those that are mapped with measure ν. So this should follow directly from the definition.

In Lean, we can prove this using the definition of HasLaw and the properties of the measure.

