The goal is to prove `diagonalHasLaw n i`, which is `HasLaw (fun ω ↦ (wignerMatrixMap n ω) i i) ν (WignerMeasure μ ν n)`.
The definition of `HasLaw` is `∃ P, P = pushforward ν (fun ω ↦ (wignerMatrixMap n ω) i i) ∧ P = ...`.
Alternatively, in Lean, `HasLaw f ν P` means that `f` is a measurable function and `P` is the pushforward of ν through `f`.

From the definition of `wignerMatrixMeasure`, we have `wignerMatrixMeasure n μ ν = Measure.map (wignerMatrixMap n) (WignerMeasure μ ν n)`.
This means that `WignerMeasure μ ν n` is the measure on `ω`, and `wignerMatrixMeasure n μ ν` is the pushforward of `WignerMeasure μ ν n` through `wignerMatrixMap n`.

To show that `fun ω ↦ (wignerMatrixMap n ω) i i` has law ν with respect to `WignerMeasure μ ν n`, we need to show that `fun ω ↦ (wignerMatrixMap n ω) i i` is measurable and that `WignerMeasure μ ν n` is the pushforward of ν through this function.

This should be true by the definition of `wignerMatrixMeasure`. Let's try to formalize this in Lean.

